.
Recap of the last year. I spent majority of the year at maintenance.
.
Last year 21’, I had been in a build, so at the beginning of this year i started a cut for 10 Weeks. I was pretty aggressive and dropped 13 lbs. it was exciting. I felt like i peeled back a lot of the body fat I had put on during my builds and i really loved seeing the added muscle i put on.
.
Later in the year I wanted to a little experiment and test a body recomp appraoch so for 4 weeks I was at a 10% deficit, I could myself tighten up a little and then I pushed the calories back up and was able to see 1% drop in body fat and a little increase in muscle over a 12 week period. 

So that was a total of 14 weeks in a calorie deficit.

I am currently I’m not tracking, I’m mindfully eating. I don’t spend all my time tracking. That would be overwhelming and I feel like tracking is a tool NOT a lifestyle.
.
I use it as a tool to lose weight or to push into a muscle building phase.
.
Now I’m using my healthy lifestyle to maintain. My weight fluctuates at maintenance, 3-4 lbs during the week but that’s totally normal to see. The overall monthly average is about the same. My abs aren’t as sharp but I can still see a 4 pack when I flex excruciatingly hard and in the right lighting 😆😉. And my arms have softened just a bit but I’m at a level of leanness I can maintain with mindful eating so this is a great spot for me.
.
Now mindful eating still requires some mental effort. Some people think it shouldn’t require any effort at all. Well that’s silly. Do we just brush our teeth once and call it good? Nope. We need daily upkeep. Do we put oil in the car once and think we can keep driving it no matter the time and distance?! Of course not! Our body is no different! Want to maintain? Then there has to be some level of thought. Should it be neurotic and obsessive? Obviously not. We want mental and emotional health, not just physical health!

Just some Sunday thoughts for you 🫶🏻.
.
I think self care looks different for everyone. My list isn’t to tell you what self care looks like for you. But maybe to encourage you to think deeper into what self care is and looks like to YOU. Doing daily things like practicing meditation, creation, journaling, prayer, learning, have truly elevated my spirits and rejuvenated me. That’s self care to me. I hope you find what fuels you too ❤️
.
My hope is that some things you may label as self care you may realize they are mere distractions from facing feelings, and dealing with hard things in the moment. Those are ways we numb out and avoid issues in our lives instead of facing things. Ignoring and numbing out only postpones the reality that one day the feelings have to be faced, realities of life must be felt with, not numbed out forever.

.

.
Have a wonderful week! ❤️❤️
.

Hopefully this can help you understand a few things…. Oh! And please refrain from telling me which version of my body you like the most. Thanks 🙏🏻 😘

1- I don’t want to always be shredded bc I don’t like the trade offs of living in that 6 pack world. It’s a vacation home I visit once in awhile. Nothing more. 
.
2- I’m okay letting my body go in and out of lower body fat percentages. The healthiest people in fitness are okay with their body fluctuating bc they have detached their value and worth from their body. They use their fitness goals as a fun way to work hard and have a fun hobby, but they don’t let any shift of weight define them.
.
3- some of us need to go into periods of calorie surplus to see the kinds of changes we want to see in our body as far as building muscle goes. Not all of us were genetically blessed with a ton of muscle or the ability to put it in quickly.
.
4- maybe you don’t have muscle and you dropped weight and are disappointed bc you can’t see muscle. Or, maybe already have the muscle but it’s just being covered a bit with body fat. That’s okay. If you want to see it you need to drop body fat. If you don’t want to make the tradeoffs of living with more restriction  then it’s not worth it to you and that’s okay too! The great thing is this is your life. And what you want should come@from within and not bc you saw a picture of someone with a 6 pack smiling and you wan their happiness and you think it’s bc of their 6 pack. It’s more than likely not.

Did you know there isn’t anything special about 7 days? If your average weight stays the same for 7 days that doesn’t mean you’ve hit a plateau with calories and need to drop them. Remember we are looking at trends over time.

.
With the way woman’s bodies fluctuate i would say 7 days doesn’t tell us all that much. We need to watch for 2-3 weeks and all the while making sure that energy in is being measuring accurately and that your energy out isn’t dropping too much due to the body trying to preserve energy.
.
After 3 weeks of stall in measurements, pictures, scale, feeling in clothes, then I would push energy out more or drop calories, all while@emphasizing sleep and more fibrous foods to make sure that hunger was in a good place and appropriate.
.
Hope this helps!!
.

I spent majority of my life ridiculously insecure about my legs, to the point that I refused to wear shorts!!! 
.
Growing up I was teased relentlessly by family, friends, and even strangers about my ‘bird legs’. I think people thought bc I was skinny that they could say whatever about my body. But the words stung so badly I grew up thinking my legs were ugly.
.
At 16 ,after a pool party i had a boy at school come down so hard about my body, even calling me gross, that I was mortified to get into a swimsuit around people after that.
.
Funny story. I let him have it. I don’t know if I have ever sworn so much at a single person in all my life but that boy got an earful and I ended by saying he wasn’t allowed to ever look or talk to me again. To this day when I think of a boy saying to my daughters what that boy said to me my blood boils. I think I might lose my cool and put my years of deadlifting to good use throwing that boy into a wall. 🤣🤣. But last year a a restaurant I had a woman rush up to me telling me she follows me and wanted to come chat. She said she was there on a date and pointed over to …that guy from high school. 😳🤣My words must still be haunting him bc he did everything to avoid eye contact and I about chocked on my drink seeing him! 🤣.
.
In college a roommate said, “you have beautiful legs.” 😳I was shocked! But As nice as compliments are , they don’t solve our own insecurities. They are bandaids on bleeding wounds that only we can heal. 
.
When I get on my podcast and talk about embracing the canvas God gave us,
I speak from a place of knowing what it feels like to be insecure, and not fully embrace parts of me. I have worked hard to put in the work to learn to love my body. I only get one. I want to love it no matter what.
.
. Self acceptance in all aspects of ourselves has to come from within. Compliments are nice but are not enough to bring about real self love. I learned to tell myself new stories. Stories built on what my legs can do. 🏋🏼‍♀️I think that’s why I  love lifting weights so much. I feel so strong and capable!
.
Hitting 500# on a leg press I now look down at my legs and say “I love you!” 🥰

I posted myself drinking @corepower that has 42g of protein …. And then  i got a few people bringing up the whole protein absorption fallacy. “But Lindsay! can’t the body only absorb 30g protein at a time? Why are you drinking more than that isn’t it just a waste? Aren’t you just peeing it out?”
.
Swipe over to read where this comes from and what we really need to focus on!
.
✅ also, this post is about absorption which is actually slightly different than the discussion of Muscle Protein Synthesis ceilings. So if we were to say is there a cap on how much protein in one sitting can contribute to muscle protein synthesis then yes, that’s true. BUT what that is depends on the person. It can be a cap of 20-45 depending on the individual.
.
For example, in this study PMID 27511985 - trained individuals had a higher MPS response to 40g protein vs 20g.
.
Best to find your protein target, to hit it best you can throughout the day. If you’re a more advanced lifter then try for even distribution of protein 25g+. 
.
For a full breakdown of this topic, check out the link in my bio to listen to my podcast episode on it all!
.

There is a lot of nuance to program design. But here are somethings to think about when choosing your rep ranges.
.
A lot of people enjoy the higher rep range bc you can experience a nice pump with it. But we can’t always be seeking the pump or we’ll plateau.
.

I never talk much about my hashimotos because I know how incredibly individual each body responds to it. But I do feel there are some things that are very important that I can share because there are some things those of us who have it do have in common. 
.
1 - we need to prioritize building muscle. That will help our thyroid perform all the functions it’s supposed to. If we want a healthier metabolism we need to prioritize muscle building. 
.
2- Many woman with hashimotos are frustrated because their metabolism can feel slower. Stop living in a calorie deficit. You have to spend more time in maintenance than you do in a calorie deficit every year. Low energy availability will reduce t3 levels. If this is you you need to move back to maintenance and sit there for 6+ months and make sure your thyroid is in a healthier place again. This isn’t wasted time. This is prime time for building muscle. Too many people touch maintenance for a week and then jump back into a calorie deficit. That’s not enough time for your thyroid levels to rise back to where they need to be to thrive. 
. 
3- Stop doing all the HIIT. Our body doesn’t recover very well. So 4 days a week of lifting PLUS hit 2x + a week can be the exact thing draining you of your energy and lowering your thyroid levels. Prioritize sleep and recover. Priories weights and walking, only bringing in lower intensity cardio for cardiovascular health. 
.
Hope this helps!
.
